 Norman origin): habitational name from Cogan near Cardiff, which may have been named with a Welsh word meaning ‘bowl, depression’. In 1166 Milo de Cogan, held two fees near Penarth (Glamorganshire) of William earl of Gloucester. Members of this Norman family probably account for the name's appearance in 13th-century Berwickshire. By this time the family was also present in Ireland, associated with counties Limerick and Cork. It may have been the Irish branch that later brought the name to southwest Scotland.","Irish (Leitrim): variant of   Coogan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cogen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Dorith.  German Erwin.","Variant of   Cogan  ."]},{"name":"Coggin","meanings":["English: variant of   Cogan  ."]},{"name":"Cohen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Isadore, Emanuel, Moshe, Shlomo, Myer, Avi, Yehuda, Chaim.","Jewish: from Hebrew <i>kohen</i> ‘priest’. Priests are traditionally regarded as members of a hereditary caste descended from Aaron, brother of Moses. See also   Kaplan  .","Irish (Galway and Sligo): variant of   Coyne  ."]},{"name":"Coggins","meanings":["English: variant of   Cogan  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Coggan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Conal, Seamus.  Jewish Hyman.","English: variant of   Cogan  .","Americanized form of Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic) <b>Kogan</b>, from the Russian pronunciation of   Cohen  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Cogan was born in 1200, in Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales as the son of Richard de Cogan. He had at least 1 son. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1200–":"1200–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1164–1238":"1164–1238","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1164":"1164","1283":"1283","Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"1200–":"1200–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1164–1238":"1164–1238","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1164":"1164","1283":"1283","Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"1200–":"1200–Décédé","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1164–1238":"1164–1238","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1164":"1164","1283":"1283","Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cogan, Glamorgan, Galles","lifeSummary":"William de Cogan est né en 1200, à Cogan, Glamorgan, Galles, fils de Richard de Cogan. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1200–":"1200–Verstorben","1200–Male":"1200–Verstorben","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1164–1238":"1164–1238","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1164":"1164","1283":"1283","Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales","lifeSummary":"William de Cogan wurde 1200 in Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales, als Sohn von Richard de Cogan geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb in seinem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1200–":"1200–Desede","1200–Male":"1200–Desede","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1164–1238":"1164–1238","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1164":"1164","1283":"1283","Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales":"Cogan, Glamorgan, Wales"},"hu":{"1200–":"1200–elhunyt","1200–Male":"1200–elhunyt","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1164–1238":"1164–1238","1238